  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Williamson argues against dominant 20th-century views that would reduce philosophy to linguistic analysis, conceptual analysis, or culturally relative inquiry. He defends a robustly realist conception of philosophy as continuous with other forms of inquiry, particularly with science, employing a broadly abductive methodology that seeks the best explanations of all the evidence (including evidence from thought experiments, intuitions, and reflection). Philosophy, on this view, aims at knowledge of objective, mind-independent reality, and philosophical method is not fundamentally distinct from scientific method.

  RELEVANCE: Williamson's defense of philosophical methodology has significant implications for how literature reviews in philosophy should be conceived. If philosophy is continuous with science and employs broadly abductive methods, then literature reviews might function similarly to reviews in empirical sciences—surveying evidence, assessing competing explanatory theories, identifying unsolved problems. However, if philosophical "evidence" includes intuitions, conceptual considerations, and thought experiments, the criteria for appraising and synthesizing this evidence will differ from empirical research, raising questions about what a "systematic" philosophical review would involve.

  POSITION: Methodological continuity between philosophy and science. Rejects linguistic turn and defends philosophy as knowledge-seeking enterprise with methods continuous with (though not identical to) scientific inquiry. Implies literature reviews should survey philosophical "evidence" and assess competing theories, though details of how this works remain to be specified.
  },
  keywords = {metaphilosophy, philosophical-method, naturalism, High},
  abstract = {Preface. Acknowledgments. Introduction. 1. The Linguistic Turn and the Conceptual Turn. 2. Taking Philosophical Questions at Face Value. 3. Metaphysical Conceptions of Analyticity. 4. Epistemological Conceptions of Analyticity. 5. Knowledge of Metaphysical Modality. 6. Thought Experiments. 7. Evidence in Philosophy. 8. Knowledge Maximization. Afterword. Must Do Better. Appendix 1. Modal Logic within Counterfactual Logic. Appendix 2. Counterfactual Donkeys. Bibliography. Index},
  abstract_source = {openalex},
  iep_context = {IEP Metaphilosophy article cites Williamson (2007) in section "Defining Metaphilosophy" to illustrate the first-order view of metaphilosophy: "Metaphilosophy, as the application of philosophy to philosophy itself, is simply one more instance of philosophy (Wittgenstein 2001: section 121; Williamson 2007: ix)." Williamson takes the first-order view and prefers the term "the philosophy of philosophy" to "metaphilosophy," believing that "metaphilosophy" connotes a second-order perspective that "looks down upon philosophy from above, or beyond"—a connotation he rejects.},
}
